<h1>💎 RS004 Week 12 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Coin Types + Spin Animation (Apply) · <strong>Course:</strong> Platformer Game · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>This week coins come in <strong>kinds</strong> — gold (1 point), gem (5), secret (10). Each coin is stored as a <strong>dictionary</strong> with its rect, kind, and value, and they <strong>spin</strong> with a <code>sin</code> wave that wobbles their width. On this worksheet you think about and explain that code in English — you don't type or run anything.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Keep these words handy: <strong>dictionary</strong>, <strong>kind / value</strong>, <strong><code>math.sin</code></strong>, <strong>wobble (animate)</strong>, <strong>frame</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each snippet and write what you think it does.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">coins = [
    {&quot;rect&quot;: pygame.Rect(180, 480, 20, 20), &quot;kind&quot;: &quot;gold&quot;, &quot;value&quot;: 1},
    {&quot;rect&quot;: pygame.Rect(580, 480, 20, 20), &quot;kind&quot;: &quot;gem&quot;,  &quot;value&quot;: 5},
]
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Each coin is now a dictionary. How do you read the second coin's value?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">wave = math.sin(frame * 0.1) * 8
w = max(2, int(20 + wave))
</code></pre>
<p><strong><code>math.sin(...)</code> swings between -1 and +1. What is the smallest the width <code>w</code> can get, and why the <code>max(2, ...)</code>?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">if player.colliderect(coin[&quot;rect&quot;]):
    score = score + coin[&quot;value&quot;]
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The player grabs a gem. How much does the score go up?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Read the Dictionary 🗂️</h2>
<p>A coin is <code>{"rect": pygame.Rect(450, 250, 20, 20), "kind": "secret", "value": 10}</code>. Fill in the blanks.</p>
<pre><code>coin[&quot;kind&quot;]   = ___
coin[&quot;value&quot;]  = ___
coin[&quot;rect&quot;].x = ___
</code></pre>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why is a dictionary better than three separate lists (one for rects, one for kinds, one for values)?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each snippet is broken. Rewrite it so it works, then explain why the original was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — Every coin should add its own value, but all coins add 1 point no matter the kind.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">for coin in coins[:]:
    if player.colliderect(coin[&quot;rect&quot;]):
        score = score + 1
        coins.remove(coin)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> use <code>coin["value"]</code>, not a fixed <code>1</code>.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — The collision check should compare the player with the coin's rectangle, but it crashes saying a dict can't collide.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">for coin in coins[:]:
    if player.colliderect(coin):
        score += coin[&quot;value&quot;]
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the rect lives inside the dictionary under a key.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — The coins should keep wobbling, but they spin once and then freeze.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">def draw_coin(coin, frame):
    wave = math.sin(frame * 0.1) * 8
    w = max(2, int(20 + wave))
    ...
# in the game loop:
frame = 0
draw_coin(coin, frame)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> <code>frame</code> never increases, so <code>sin</code> never changes. Where should <code>frame</code> grow?</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
